canonical:
  title: 朱祝大夫起復
  author: 崔致遠
  language: lzh
  text: 牒奉處分事繁金革禮奪苴麻魯公制之於前晉侯行之於後盖乃從權順變是爲移孝就忠苟不忘家將何報國前件官方從戎役每藉公才遽鍾風樹之悲永違霜槿之養能勤泣血唯懼奪情然以群寇未殲列藩多事礭執三年之愛仰辜萬乘之恩况承勑命指揮已許軍前驅使出如綸之睿旨旣俟成功衣夫錦之格言豈同前哲時異事異念玆在玆揚名顯親竭力從命孝之終也往矣敬哉事須牒擧起復差往五嶺已來類會軍前公事
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 朱祝大夫起復
  author: 崔致遠
  language: lzh
  text: 牒奉處分。事繁金革。禮奪苴麻。魯公制之於前。晉侯行之於後。盖乃從權順變。是爲移孝就忠。苟不忘家。將何報國。前件官。方從戎役。每藉公才。遽鍾風樹之悲。永違霜槿之養。能勤泣血。唯懼奪情。然以群寇未殲。列藩多事。礭執三年之愛。仰辜萬乘之恩。况承勑命指揮。已許軍前驅使。出如綸之睿旨。旣俟成功。衣夫錦之格言。豈同前哲。時異事異。念玆在玆。揚名顯親。竭力從命。孝之終也。往矣敬哉。事須牒擧起復差往五嶺已來類會軍前公事。
korean:
  title: 주축대부 기복
  author: 최치원
  language: kor
  text: 처분을 받들어 통첩한다. 전쟁이 일어나 일이 번잡할 때는, 예(禮)가 저마(苴麻 상복〈喪服〉)를 빼앗으니, 이 제도는 전에 노공(魯公)이 만들었고, 진후(晉侯)가 그뒤에 시행하였다. 대개 권도(權道)에 좇아서 순변(順變)해 나가는 것으로, 이것은 효도를 옮겨서 충성에 나아가는 것이다. 진실로 집을 잊지 않으면 장차 어찌 나라에 보답하리오. 전건의 주축대부는 그 전에 병역(兵役)에 종사할 적에 매양 공직에 있었는데, 갑자기 어버이가 돌아가시는 슬픔을 만나, 영원히 부모 봉양하는 길을 어겼다. 그래서 언제나 피눈물을 흘리며 울면서 오직 나라에서 사정(私情)을 빼앗지는 않을까 두려워하였다. 그러나, 뭇 도적을 다 잡지 못함으로써 여러 번진(藩鎭)에 일이 많으니, 여기에 3년의 집상을 고집하게 되면, 임금의 은혜를 저버리는 것이 된다. 하물며, 칙명(勅命)이 이미 그에게 군전(軍前)에 나와서 일을 하라고 하였음에랴. 임금의 교지(敎旨)가 이러한 것은 성공을 기다리는 것이다. “비단 옷을 입고 상복을 벗어서는 안 된다.”는 공자의 말씀과는 그 때가 다르고 일이 다르니, 이것을 잘 생각하여야 할 것이다. 이름을 떨쳐서 부모를 드러나게 하고, 힘을 다하여 임금의 명을 좇는 것이 효도의 완성이니, 가서 조심해서 할지어다. 마땅히 그를 기복(起復)시켜 오령(五嶺)에 가서 군전공사(軍前公事)를 맡게 하라.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1090_010_0310&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Restoration to Office of Chu, the Grand Master
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    An official dispatch is hereby issued. When warfare erupts and duties multiply, propriety itself yields to necessity—the mourning robes are set aside. This precedent was established by Duke Lu in ages past, and carried forward by the Marquis of Jin thereafter. Thus do we follow the path of expediency and adapt to changing times, redirecting filial devotion toward loyal service to the state. Yet should one forget his home entirely, how could he repay his nation?

    The aforementioned Grand Master, when previously engaged in military service, ever served with distinction. But suddenly grief descended upon him—the loss of his parents—severing him from the way of filial care. Since then he has wept tears of blood, fearing only that the state would demand his heart.

    Yet consider: the bandits remain unvanquished, troubles multiply in the provinces. To insist upon three years of mourning would be to betray the sovereign's grace. Moreover, the imperial mandate itself has commanded him to duties at the front. The sage's teachings speak of not removing mourning garments even for silk robes—but times change, circumstances differ. Let wisdom discern this well.

    To honor one's name and illuminate one's parents while dedicating all strength to the sovereign's command—this is the perfection of filial piety. Go forth with reverence and care. Let it be proclaimed that he is hereby restored to office and dispatched to the Five Ridges to assume command of military affairs.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Ridges (五嶺) refers to a mountainous region in southern China, here likely representing the military frontier zone where this official was to serve.
  - key: ''
    value: The conflict between filial duty and loyalty to the state was a central tension in Confucian ethics; this dispatch attempts to reconcile them by arguing that true filial piety extends to serving one's country.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "not removing mourning garments even for silk robes" alludes to Confucian teachings on maintaining ritual propriety during mourning periods.
